'''Misono Kofun''' (美園古墳) is a {{ill|Kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft}} (ancient Kofun) located in {{ill|Yao|ja|八尾市|12=draft}}, Osaka Prefecture. This square tumulus was identified as one of the buried remains beneath the planned site of the {{ill|Kinki Expressway|ja|近畿自動車道|12=draft}}. Despite its small size, the mound yielded a notable collection of burial goods, including large-map_size house-shaped and jar-shaped {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪|12=draft}}, Historic Site1 as [[{{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|ko|일본의_중요문화재|12=draft}} of Japan]].

== Overview ==

In 1981, during the excavation of the {{ill|Misono Ruins|ja|美園遺跡|12=draft}}, a multi-period site spanning the {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|12=draft}} to the medieval era, remains of a square tumulus (7.2 m per side) were discovered. Most of the mound had been leveled, and no burial facility was found. However, cylindrical and figurative haniwa were unearthed from a moat approximately 2 meters wide surrounding the mound.

== House-shaped and Jar-shaped Haniwa ==

The excavated haniwa include two detailed house-shaped haniwa and over 25 jar-shaped haniwa. 

One house-shaped haniwa, recovered from the northern corner of the moat, replicates a {{ill|Irimoya-style|ja|入母屋造|12=draft}} elevated-floor building (approximately 2 x 2 bays). Measuring 70 cm in height, it features a ridge length of 75 cm, maximum eave length of 55 cm, and beam length of 45 cm. The surface and parts of the interior were coated in red ochre. Notable details include a bed-like structure raised 3.5 cm from the floor and shield engravings on the outer walls, decorated with serrated motifs. Scholars suggest this haniwa faithfully depicts the residence of a chief.

The second house-shaped haniwa represents a {{ill|Kirizuma-style|ja|切妻造|12=draft}} building (approximately 2 x 2 bays) interpreted as a storage structure. Measuring 31 cm in height, with a ridge length of 60 cm and maximum eave and beam lengths of 42 cm and 38 cm respectively, its surface was similarly coated in red ochre.

The jar-shaped haniwa resemble morning-glory-shaped cylindrical haniwa. With 10 cm diameter holes pre-typeed at their bases, they were designed as ceremonial haniwa rather than functional jars.

Three of these haniwa (two house-shaped and one jar-shaped) are Historic Site1 as National {{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|ko|일본의_중요문화재|12=draft}}, held by the Cultural Affairs Agency and preserved at the Osaka Prefectural Chikatsu Asuka Museum.

<gallery>
File:美園古墳出土_家形埴輪.JPG|House-shaped haniwa<br/>{{small|Photographed during a special exhibit at the {{ill|Kashihara Archaeological Institute|ja|奈良県立橿原考古学研究所|12=draft}}.}}
</gallery>

== Historic Site ==

=== National {{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|ko|일본의_중요문화재|12=draft}} ===
* Two house-shaped haniwa and three jar-shaped haniwa, excavated from Misono Kofun, Yao City, Osaka Prefecture (archaeological material) - Designated on June 15, 1995.<ref>{{国cultural property等データベース|201|10118|House-shaped and Jar-shaped Haniwa from Misono Kofun, Yao City, Osaka}}</ref>

